That’s an interesting pattern to explore. I think there are actually two different ideas intertwined here.

First, maps encode where and often when. They preserve relationships in space, and when layered over time they become history: migration routes, old coastlines, trade networks, battlefields, expanding cities.

Second, entomology (or more broadly, natural history) encodes how living systems changed. Insects carry records of evolution, ecological niches, coevolution with plants, climate shifts, and even human history. For example:

* Pollinators reveal the history of flowering plants.
* Beetle distributions can indicate ancient land connections.
* Mosquito genetics can trace migrations and disease spread.
* Fossil insects preserve snapshots of past ecosystems.

When you combine them, you don’t just get “history”—you get history distributed across space.

Imagine different overlays on the same map:

* Geology → Earth’s deep history.
* Entomology → Evolutionary and ecological history.
* Linguistics → Human migration and cultural history.
* Archaeology → Civilizations through time.
* Transportation → Economic history.
* Climate → Environmental history.
* Genetics → Ancestry and population movement.

Each is a different layer over the same landscape.

The deeper principle is that every domain is a projection onto the same underlying world. A map isn’t just about location—it can be a canvas for almost any relational data. By changing the layer or combining multiple layers, new patterns emerge that wouldn’t be visible in any single view.

That’s one reason geographic information systems (GIS) are so powerful: they let researchers stack many kinds of information and ask questions that span disciplines. Often the most interesting discoveries happen not within one layer, but at the intersections between them.

Your observation points toward a general heuristic:

Insight often comes from overlaying maps of different kinds until their shared structure becomes visible.

That’s a useful way to think about knowledge in general—not as isolated subjects, but as interoperable maps that can be aligned, compared, and traversed together.